<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-07-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-07-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="437" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d437">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Jackson</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy
                                        of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-07-05"><hi rend="italic">July 5,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1998.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to previous correspondence, I
                            have the honor to inform you that a note has just been received from the
                            German foreign office in which it is stated that permission is granted
                            the Eisemann brothers to remain in Frankfort-on-the-Main until the 1st
                            of next April.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John B. Jackson.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>